WEBVTT

00:04.569 --> 00:06.049
- Quantum Leap was
an experimental

00:06.093 --> 00:08.573
time travel program,
years away from being tested.

00:08.617 --> 00:10.445
Why did you leap?
- I don't remember anything.

00:10.488 --> 00:11.924
- Your name is Dr. Ben Song.

00:11.968 --> 00:13.970
You're a time traveler
leaping from life to life,

00:14.014 --> 00:15.798
trying to put right
what once went wrong.

00:15.841 --> 00:16.973
I'm Addison Augustine.

00:17.017 --> 00:19.584
- Addison.
You're the woman I love.

00:19.628 --> 00:21.151
- Ben's working with someone.

00:21.195 --> 00:23.153
- Al Calavicci's daughter,
Janis.

00:23.197 --> 00:24.937
- What is that?
- That's the destination.

00:24.981 --> 00:27.418
I think that Ben was trying
to leap into the future,

00:27.462 --> 00:29.855
to a specific place,
a specific point in time.

00:29.899 --> 00:31.074
- That shouldn't be possible.

00:31.118 --> 00:33.207
- I remember
why I leapt the first place.

00:33.250 --> 00:36.079
It's to save you.

00:36.123 --> 00:37.341
- Janis is here to help us.

00:37.385 --> 00:38.647
- I'm gonna give you a name,

00:38.690 --> 00:40.127
the name of the person
who told Ben to leap

00:40.170 --> 00:41.519
in the first place.

00:44.566 --> 00:46.176
[LMFAO's
"Party Rock Anthem" playing]

00:46.220 --> 00:48.439
[indistinct cheering]

00:48.483 --> 00:51.268
[ball bouncing,
shoes squeaking]

00:52.574 --> 00:54.141
[whistle blows]
- Ow.

00:54.184 --> 00:55.359
Ow.
- Are you okay?

00:55.403 --> 00:56.491
- Fine.
- There you go.

00:56.534 --> 00:58.014
- [wincing]
- You got it, come on.

00:58.058 --> 01:00.016
- Coach!

01:00.060 --> 01:01.365
What do we do?

01:01.409 --> 01:04.890
[dramatic music]

01:04.934 --> 01:06.196
- Time!

01:06.240 --> 01:08.068
Time out!
[whistle blows]

01:08.111 --> 01:09.156
- You love basketball.

01:09.199 --> 01:11.419
- I do love basketball.

01:11.462 --> 01:12.637
- Okay.
- What?

01:12.681 --> 01:14.204
- Uh, did anyone see
what happened?

01:14.248 --> 01:15.379
- I got the board
and passed to Amanda.

01:15.423 --> 01:16.554
- It was a loose ball.

01:16.598 --> 01:17.729
Amanda tried to save it
and went down.

01:17.773 --> 01:19.601
- I just landed
on it funny, that's all.

01:19.644 --> 01:20.471
Let's go!

01:20.515 --> 01:21.994
Ah!
- Ben, in 2012,

01:22.038 --> 01:23.561
the Lions lost this game.

01:23.605 --> 01:25.085
Marina Hills went to regionals.

01:25.128 --> 01:26.173
- Maybe we're here to win.

01:26.216 --> 01:27.478
- Of course we're here to win.

01:27.521 --> 01:28.827
- Coach, you can't
take her out.

01:28.871 --> 01:30.742
Stanford is here scouting her.
This is her game.

01:30.786 --> 01:32.657
- But look at her.
She's no good.

01:32.701 --> 01:33.832
- [wincing]

01:33.876 --> 01:35.051
Ow.
- Uh...

01:35.095 --> 01:37.184
[buzzer blares]

01:37.227 --> 01:38.140
Do we have anyone else?

01:38.185 --> 01:39.447
- No.

01:39.490 --> 01:40.970
- Everyone else is injured,
except--

01:41.013 --> 01:42.145
- 23! Come on.

01:42.189 --> 01:43.581
- No, Coach,
you can't take me out.

01:43.625 --> 01:45.322
- Amanda, you play
on that ankle again,

01:45.366 --> 01:46.628
you're out for good.

01:46.670 --> 01:51.894
♪

01:51.937 --> 01:52.895
23?

01:52.938 --> 01:54.375
- Coach.

01:54.418 --> 01:56.203
- All right.
Let's go!

01:56.246 --> 01:57.378
Gia's getting in the game!

01:57.420 --> 01:58.727
- About damn time.

01:58.770 --> 02:00.163
[crowd cheering]

02:00.207 --> 02:01.556
- Are you--
are you sure about this?

02:01.599 --> 02:03.253
- Well, yeah. You're a part
of the team, aren't you?

02:03.297 --> 02:04.428
- Yeah.
- Well, all right, then.

02:04.472 --> 02:05.821
Let's get you out there.

02:07.779 --> 02:09.128
[whistle blows]

02:09.172 --> 02:12.044
[LMFAO's
"Party Rock Anthem" resumes]

02:12.088 --> 02:15.004
♪

02:15.047 --> 02:17.398
Watch the ball, watch the ball,
watch the ball.

02:17.441 --> 02:19.574
Okay. Let's see that screen.

02:21.010 --> 02:22.098
Board, board, board!

02:22.142 --> 02:23.186
Ah.

02:23.230 --> 02:25.275
[crowd cheering]

02:25.319 --> 02:27.059
[whistle blows]
Come on, come on, come on.

02:27.103 --> 02:29.279
Set a screen for three.

02:29.323 --> 02:31.151
Do it, do it, do it, do it.

02:32.716 --> 02:33.892
That's you--ah.

02:33.936 --> 02:35.198
It's okay, it's okay.
We'll get it back.

02:35.242 --> 02:37.505
We'll get it back.
One stop, one stop.

02:38.723 --> 02:40.072
- Block her!

02:40.116 --> 02:41.335
- Backboard, backboard!

02:41.378 --> 02:43.641
all: Eight, seven,

02:43.685 --> 02:46.166
six, five, four,

02:46.209 --> 02:49.343
three, two, one.

02:50.300 --> 02:52.259
[buzzer blares]

02:52.302 --> 02:54.783
[crowd cheering]

02:54.826 --> 02:57.742
[triumphant music]

02:57.786 --> 03:00.049
♪

03:00.092 --> 03:01.137
- [laughing]

03:01.181 --> 03:02.225
- Yes!

03:02.269 --> 03:04.532
[crowd booing]

03:04.575 --> 03:05.794
- Hey, that's not fair!

03:05.837 --> 03:07.839
- Cheaters!
- That's not fair!

03:07.883 --> 03:09.928
- Unfair! Boo!

03:09.972 --> 03:11.930
[overlapping jeers]

03:11.974 --> 03:13.062
- What are they booing at?

03:13.105 --> 03:14.933
- Ben, Gia's trans.

03:18.154 --> 03:19.547
- Gia--
- Whatever, Dad.

03:20.896 --> 03:22.202
- Gia--

03:23.594 --> 03:24.813
- And she's your daughter.

03:26.902 --> 03:29.861
[intense music]

03:29.905 --> 03:32.864
♪

03:32.908 --> 03:35.867
[tense music]

03:35.911 --> 03:41.395
♪

03:41.438 --> 03:43.223
- What am I doing here, Carlos?

03:43.266 --> 03:44.528
- I'm just saying,

03:44.572 --> 03:46.356
I still don't think he should
have put her in.

03:46.400 --> 03:47.704
- We won the game, Amanda.

03:47.749 --> 03:49.793
We're one away from regionals.

03:49.838 --> 03:51.535
- It is a little weird though,
isn't it?

03:51.579 --> 03:53.189
Coach waits this long
to put his own kid in the game.

03:53.233 --> 03:55.452
- She's an alternate.
That's how alternates work.

03:55.496 --> 03:56.714
- She's been on the team
all season.

03:56.758 --> 03:58.281
- And you never had
an issue before.

03:58.325 --> 03:59.369
- And I don't have
an issue now.

03:59.413 --> 04:00.501
I'm just saying,
it's a little weird.

04:00.544 --> 04:02.111
- Well, I have an issue.

04:02.154 --> 04:03.243
I don't think it's fair.

04:03.286 --> 04:04.679
- Why, 'cause she's trans,

04:04.722 --> 04:06.071
or because she took your shot?

04:06.115 --> 04:07.856
- I don't know, both?

04:07.899 --> 04:11.033
- [scoffs]
- Way to be a team player.

04:11.076 --> 04:12.948
[Fun.'s "We Are Young" playing]

04:12.991 --> 04:15.385
- Coach Carlos, a word?

04:15.429 --> 04:16.908
We discussed this, did we not?

04:16.952 --> 04:17.995
- Yeah, of course we did.

04:18.040 --> 04:19.084
- What did you think
was gonna happen

04:19.128 --> 04:20.084
when you put Gia in the game?

04:20.129 --> 04:21.913
- I was kind of hoping
we'd win.

04:21.957 --> 04:24.568
- I have to keep this whole
school together, Mr. Mendez.

04:24.612 --> 04:27.484
I have budget cuts, the PTA,
and the school board.

04:27.528 --> 04:28.616
Don't ask me to fight

04:28.659 --> 04:29.747
a culture war
for your daughter.

04:29.791 --> 04:31.532
Ain't nobody got time for that.

04:31.575 --> 04:33.838
Just do your job
and get the team to regionals.

04:33.882 --> 04:35.275
Keep your kid out of it.

04:35.318 --> 04:38.408
[tense music]

04:38.452 --> 04:40.497
- Mandy, Amanda, baby.
- Mom, I'm fine.

04:40.541 --> 04:42.586
I just wrapped it to be safe.

04:42.630 --> 04:43.892
- She could have stayed
in the game.

04:43.935 --> 04:44.936
We had scouts out there.

04:44.980 --> 04:47.112
- My only concern
was her safety.

04:47.156 --> 04:48.592
You don't want your daughter
playing with an injury.

04:48.636 --> 04:50.028
- Don't tell me
how to parent my child.

04:50.072 --> 04:51.769
- I--I wasn't--

04:51.813 --> 04:55.512
♪

04:55.556 --> 04:57.079
Hey, is Gia in there?
- Coach, you know she's not

04:57.122 --> 04:58.907
allowed to change with us.
[door opens]

05:04.391 --> 05:06.001
- Somebody ask for a mop?

05:09.831 --> 05:11.659
- Okay, so everyone knew
that she was trans.

05:11.702 --> 05:13.182
- Yeah.
I mean, some families might not

05:13.225 --> 05:15.010
be completely open
about their kid's transition,

05:15.053 --> 05:17.317
which is fine, because it's
actually nobody's business.

05:17.360 --> 05:19.144
But Gia got a lot of attention

05:19.188 --> 05:22.104
when her dad was hired
to coach at Lakehill--

05:22.147 --> 05:23.801
I don't know for sports,
but when Lakehill Theater

05:23.845 --> 05:25.455
did "Miss Saigon,"
they used a real helicopter.

05:25.499 --> 05:26.456
It was riveting.

05:26.500 --> 05:27.544
- Wait, did you go there?

05:27.588 --> 05:28.850
- No, I went to Rancho.

05:28.893 --> 05:29.981
We had Model UN.

05:30.025 --> 05:31.113
- But you knew her?

05:31.156 --> 05:32.419
- Well, I knew ofher.

05:32.462 --> 05:34.769
She was legendary,
at least to me.

05:34.812 --> 05:37.075
And when she won the game,
and it was all over the news--

05:37.119 --> 05:38.642
- Wait, wait, wait.
The game that she just won?

05:38.686 --> 05:40.383
- Yeah, it was iconic

05:40.427 --> 05:42.429
before we even
called things iconic.

05:42.472 --> 05:44.692
- Ian, Gia only played

05:44.735 --> 05:46.694
because Ben put her in
right now.

05:46.737 --> 05:47.999
As soon as she was
on the court,

05:48.043 --> 05:49.218
Ziggy started updating.

05:49.261 --> 05:50.915
- I've been bested
by my own technology.

05:52.308 --> 05:55.832
Um, okay, so then what was
the original story?

05:55.877 --> 05:58.488
- Uh, originally,
instead of putting his daughter

05:58.532 --> 06:01.404
in the game, Coach Carlos
played shorthanded.

06:01.448 --> 06:03.275
They lost, and--
and Gia ran away.

06:03.319 --> 06:04.973
- Oh, no.

06:05.016 --> 06:07.367
- What--no, no, no.
They won the game.

06:07.410 --> 06:08.411
I mean, we're now
in a completely

06:08.455 --> 06:09.499
different timeline.
That's--

06:09.543 --> 06:12.328
- I still remember
Gia running away.

06:12.372 --> 06:15.375
No one ever heard
from her again.

06:15.418 --> 06:16.593
- Okay. What do we do?

06:16.637 --> 06:18.900
- Well, uh, Ziggy and I will
do some digging.

06:18.943 --> 06:20.641
But I think what Gia needs now,

06:20.684 --> 06:22.382
more than anything,
is an accomplice.

06:22.425 --> 06:23.861
- Like an ally?
- No, no.

06:23.905 --> 06:25.994
Allies, they sit in the
bleachers, they wave a flag.

06:26.037 --> 06:28.431
An accomplice actually has
skin in the game.

06:28.475 --> 06:29.519
- Was that a sports metaphor?

06:29.563 --> 06:31.086
- Yeah, I know.
I'm really trying.

06:31.129 --> 06:32.870
- Yeah, good job. Okay.

06:34.611 --> 06:36.700
[upbeat music playing softly]

06:36.744 --> 06:38.093
- You sure this
is the right spot?

06:38.136 --> 06:40.835
Doesn't seem like
Ben's kind of place.

06:40.878 --> 06:42.706
- It isn't.
According to Janis,

06:42.750 --> 06:44.447
six months before he leapt,

06:44.491 --> 06:46.493
someone named Dottie
reached out to Ben

06:46.536 --> 06:47.755
and told him to meet them here.

06:47.798 --> 06:49.365
- Where'd this come from?
- I hacked into

06:49.409 --> 06:52.586
the closed-circuit security
video to confirm Janis' story.

06:52.629 --> 06:54.065
- We're out of oat milk
and growlers.

06:54.109 --> 06:55.763
- Yeah, we're looking
for Dottie.

06:55.806 --> 06:57.939
- Who's we?
- Just some old friends.

06:57.982 --> 06:59.462
- [chuckles]
That's funny,

06:59.506 --> 07:02.552
'cause I'm Dottie,
and we're not friends.

07:02.596 --> 07:04.249
- Well, we're in that, uh,

07:04.293 --> 07:07.252
"stranger is a friend
you haven't met yet" category.

07:07.296 --> 07:08.471
- We need your help.

07:08.515 --> 07:10.908
Do you remember meeting
with this man?

07:10.952 --> 07:12.388
- This is from
our security cameras.

07:12.432 --> 07:14.608
Where'd you get this?
- That part's not important.

07:14.651 --> 07:17.262
If you could just tell us
what you remember.

07:17.306 --> 07:19.700
- I have no idea who that is.

07:19.743 --> 07:21.789
- We have it
from a reliable source

07:21.832 --> 07:23.573
that you spoke with this man,

07:23.617 --> 07:26.489
Dr. Ben Song, right here.

07:26.533 --> 07:28.360
- [scoffs]
Well, I have it

07:28.404 --> 07:31.059
from a reliable source
that my subversive poetry has

07:31.102 --> 07:33.104
gotten me
on government watch lists.

07:33.148 --> 07:34.236
So whose reliable source

07:34.279 --> 07:36.107
do you think
I'm relying on right now?

07:36.151 --> 07:38.806
- Subversive poetry?

07:38.849 --> 07:40.372
- Come back tomorrow night,

07:40.416 --> 07:43.941
if you can handle
a venti cold brew of the truth.

07:43.985 --> 07:48.032
- Please, the date on this
photo is March 13th, 2022.

07:48.076 --> 07:49.294
[metal clatters]

07:49.338 --> 07:51.079
- Did you say March 13th?

07:51.122 --> 07:52.602
[tense music]

07:52.646 --> 07:54.778
That was the week that I, uh--

07:54.822 --> 07:57.781
- Does that date mean
something to you?

07:57.825 --> 07:59.261
- Who are you people?

07:59.304 --> 08:02.133
- Tell us what you know,
we'll tell you what we can.

08:02.177 --> 08:04.048
♪

08:04.092 --> 08:05.485
- Look, I can't talk
about it now, all right?

08:05.528 --> 08:07.051
Management here is sus.

08:07.095 --> 08:09.053
But come back
to the poetry slam.

08:09.097 --> 08:10.315
We'll talk after.

08:10.359 --> 08:14.972
♪

08:18.585 --> 08:20.587
- We're home.

08:20.630 --> 08:22.589
- How'd it go?

08:22.632 --> 08:23.894
- Hi, Umma.

08:23.938 --> 08:24.895
Don't act like
your phone hasn't

08:24.939 --> 08:26.418
been blowing up all night.

08:26.462 --> 08:28.682
- I heard you scored
the final shot of the game.

08:28.725 --> 08:31.293
- I guess
good news travels fast.

08:31.336 --> 08:32.686
- Why don't you go get
washed up for dinner?

08:32.729 --> 08:34.034
I'll call you when it's ready.

08:34.078 --> 08:35.210
- Okay.

08:37.821 --> 08:38.822
- And no "Angry Birds."

08:38.866 --> 08:41.085
- [scoffs] Yes, Mom.

08:41.129 --> 08:42.696
- Kitchen--now.

08:44.654 --> 08:47.570
[soft dramatic music]

08:47.614 --> 08:52.183
♪

08:52.227 --> 08:54.751
I would have appreciated
a heads-up.

08:54.795 --> 08:56.579
- Yeah, uh, about that--

08:56.623 --> 08:57.928
- I can't believe
you put her in the game

08:57.972 --> 08:59.321
without checking with me first.

08:59.364 --> 09:00.670
- There was an injury,

09:00.714 --> 09:01.845
and our team was down a player.

09:01.889 --> 09:03.673
- I don't care about the team.

09:03.717 --> 09:04.761
I care about our daughter.

09:04.805 --> 09:06.371
We have kept her out
of the spotlight

09:06.415 --> 09:07.895
for a reason.

09:07.938 --> 09:09.940
- Right. Remind me
of that reasoning again.

09:09.984 --> 09:11.725
- Oh, this isn't a joke,
Carlos.

09:11.768 --> 09:13.596
We can't let her play
in the regionals.

09:13.640 --> 09:14.858
It's only gonna
make her a target.

09:14.902 --> 09:16.425
- But she loves it.

09:16.468 --> 09:18.209
You should have seen the way
she came alive out there--

09:18.253 --> 09:20.690
- Don't do that.
Don't make me the enemy.

09:20.734 --> 09:21.865
You get to make her happy,

09:21.909 --> 09:23.563
and I have to deal
with the fallout?

09:23.606 --> 09:24.607
That is not fair.

09:24.651 --> 09:25.956
What am I supposed to do

09:26.000 --> 09:28.524
when she calls me
from school in tears

09:28.568 --> 09:30.613
because she can't go
from one class to the other

09:30.657 --> 09:32.702
without getting harassed?

09:32.746 --> 09:34.138
Or when Amanda's mom calls

09:34.182 --> 09:37.228
and accuses our daughter
of doping?

09:37.272 --> 09:40.144
- She did that?
- No, "Congrats on the win."

09:40.188 --> 09:42.886
"Too bad you had to miss
the game for work again."

09:42.930 --> 09:45.410
No, she literally
picked up the phone

09:45.454 --> 09:47.499
and asked about Gia's hormones,

09:47.543 --> 09:50.720
like that's somehow normal
or okay.

09:50.764 --> 09:53.418
- I'm, uh--I'm sorry.

09:53.462 --> 09:54.594
I--I didn't think it would--

09:54.637 --> 09:57.422
- That's right.

09:57.466 --> 09:59.033
You didn't think.

10:00.600 --> 10:03.254
And now we're all gonna have
to deal with the consequences.

10:05.692 --> 10:07.215
I hope the win was worth it.

10:07.258 --> 10:13.134
♪

10:14.657 --> 10:16.311
- Gettin' comfy?
- Oh.

10:18.661 --> 10:20.402
Hardly.

10:20.445 --> 10:23.666
There's not exactly a playbook
for this situation.

10:23.710 --> 10:24.928
- Mm.

10:24.972 --> 10:27.627
See what you did there, Coach.

10:27.670 --> 10:29.411
I got some more info
on Gia's family.

10:29.454 --> 10:30.891
- Hit me.

10:30.934 --> 10:33.502
- Well, so Miriam,
Gia's mother,

10:33.545 --> 10:36.070
has been an advocate for Gia
since day one--

10:36.113 --> 10:38.072
took her
to the trans care program

10:38.115 --> 10:39.682
at the LA Children's Hospital

10:39.726 --> 10:41.510
when Gia came out
in the fifth grade.

10:41.553 --> 10:43.817
Her father, Carlos--well, you--

10:43.860 --> 10:45.688
has been coaching
Gia's travel teams

10:45.732 --> 10:47.690
on both sides
of her transition.

10:47.734 --> 10:49.344
You took the job
coaching at Lakehill

10:49.387 --> 10:51.259
and moved the family
earlier this year.

10:51.302 --> 10:54.784
Apparently, Gia is the first
out trans student

10:54.828 --> 10:56.133
that the school has had.

10:56.177 --> 10:57.918
- Basketball I can do,
but what do I know

10:57.961 --> 10:59.659
about supporting a trans kid?

10:59.702 --> 11:01.269
- Probably just about as much

11:01.312 --> 11:03.663
as any other parent
of a trans kid,

11:03.706 --> 11:05.229
at least at first.

11:06.709 --> 11:09.146
[sighs]

11:09.190 --> 11:11.322
Ben, do you remember
when the Trans Ban

11:11.366 --> 11:12.584
came down in the military

11:12.628 --> 11:14.238
when I first started working
at Quantum Leap?

11:14.282 --> 11:17.111
- They banned trans people
in the military?

11:17.154 --> 11:19.330
- I mean, it--
it didn't hold up.

11:19.374 --> 11:21.158
But that's not the point.

11:21.202 --> 11:23.204
What the point is,
is that we saw it coming.

11:23.247 --> 11:26.120
And we--

11:26.163 --> 11:30.472
Ididn't say anything.

11:30.515 --> 11:35.869
We lost thousands
of soldiers and officers--

11:35.912 --> 11:38.045
honorable people

11:38.088 --> 11:42.266
that were discharged
basically overnight.

11:42.310 --> 11:44.529
- But you knew.

11:44.573 --> 11:46.444
- Yeah.
They gave us

11:46.488 --> 11:47.837
a pretty good warning.

11:47.881 --> 11:48.925
But we just let it happen.

11:48.969 --> 11:51.623
Look, I knew it was wrong.

11:51.667 --> 11:53.408
But I didn't know what to do.

11:53.451 --> 11:55.149
What could I do?
It's--

11:59.153 --> 12:02.765
It wouldn't have changed
the decisions,

12:02.809 --> 12:05.333
but maybe
if I had fought harder,

12:05.376 --> 12:07.422
then I could have
changed the lives

12:07.465 --> 12:09.250
of the people
that were in my command.

12:09.293 --> 12:11.121
And at the end of the day,
maybe that's the point.

12:11.165 --> 12:13.080
And just because it's hard

12:13.123 --> 12:14.646
doesn't mean
it's not worth doing.

12:14.690 --> 12:18.433
And we can't afford to make
that same mistake with Gia.

12:18.476 --> 12:20.217
- Why? What did Ziggy say?

12:20.261 --> 12:22.219
- It's not good.
When you put Gia in the game,

12:22.263 --> 12:24.439
it put her
on a different timeline.

12:24.482 --> 12:26.049
But she still runs away,

12:26.093 --> 12:28.225
and they never find her.

12:28.269 --> 12:31.402
You have to stop her
from running away, Ben,

12:31.446 --> 12:33.796
or else she is going
to be lost forever.

12:33.840 --> 12:37.495
♪

12:41.238 --> 12:44.198
[soft cheerful music]

12:44.241 --> 12:45.547
♪

12:45.590 --> 12:47.375
- Someone needs to shave.

12:47.418 --> 12:49.377
- You better not be
talking about me.

12:49.420 --> 12:52.032
- Hey, women have facial hair
too, you know.

12:52.075 --> 12:53.337
- Girl, what?

12:53.381 --> 12:56.165
My mother, the feminist.
- You're welcome.

12:56.210 --> 12:58.386
- So Gia, I was thinking
after breakfast,

12:58.429 --> 12:59.953
maybe we can go
shoot some hoops,

12:59.996 --> 13:01.258
you know, just the two of us.

13:01.302 --> 13:02.869
We could--
- Dad, what am I, ten?

13:02.912 --> 13:04.914
Besides, we have
the car wash today.

13:04.958 --> 13:07.264
- Oh, right, the car wash.

13:07.308 --> 13:09.397
Swag.

13:09.440 --> 13:11.007
What?
- It's your turn to take her

13:11.051 --> 13:12.574
to group this morning first.

13:12.617 --> 13:14.402
Don't forget.
- Fun, group.

13:14.445 --> 13:17.144
- You're always happy
once we get there.

13:17.187 --> 13:18.972
- So this--
this car wash thing,

13:19.015 --> 13:20.451
it's a basketball thing, or--

13:20.495 --> 13:23.498
- Carlos, you know how Margie
is about the boosters.

13:23.541 --> 13:25.065
It would be different
if anyone else were

13:25.108 --> 13:27.415
running the fundraiser,
but if we don't help out,

13:27.458 --> 13:29.025
I'll be the one
to never hear the end of it.

13:29.069 --> 13:31.245
- Plus, if I don't show up,
it'll just reinforce

13:31.288 --> 13:33.813
the idea that I'm an outsider.

13:35.292 --> 13:38.426
[indistinct chatter]

13:39.993 --> 13:42.256
- Hey.

13:42.299 --> 13:43.866
How are you?
- Good.

13:43.910 --> 13:45.433
- Good to see you.

13:45.476 --> 13:47.087
I heard about the game
yesterday.

13:47.130 --> 13:48.262
Congrats on the win.

13:48.305 --> 13:50.264
How are we feeling?

13:50.307 --> 13:51.961
- We're okay.
- [huffs]

13:52.005 --> 13:54.398
She's strong,

13:54.442 --> 13:55.965
even when she shouldn't
have to be.

13:56.009 --> 13:57.575
- Yeah, I know she is.

13:57.619 --> 13:59.795
Well, look,
you're not in this alone.

13:59.839 --> 14:01.971
You know the community
is here for you.

14:02.015 --> 14:03.930
And I'm here for you too.

14:03.973 --> 14:04.887
- I know.

14:06.933 --> 14:08.848
- Wanna go hang out
with your friends?

14:08.891 --> 14:09.979
- Yeah.

14:10.023 --> 14:11.328
- Bella Swan wouldn't
stand a chance

14:11.372 --> 14:13.113
against Katniss Everdeen.
That's all I'm saying.

14:13.156 --> 14:14.375
Hey, Gia.

14:14.418 --> 14:16.420
- I gave your wife
my number last week.

14:16.464 --> 14:18.335
If you ever need to chat
outside of the group,

14:18.379 --> 14:19.467
I'm here.

14:19.510 --> 14:20.772
That goes for Gia too.

14:20.816 --> 14:22.905
I know she's having
a hard time.

14:22.949 --> 14:24.733
- Yeah. Thank you.

14:24.776 --> 14:27.257
- Bella is totally useless
without Edward and Jacob.

14:27.301 --> 14:30.521
- Are you saying the odds
may not be ever in her favor?

14:30.565 --> 14:31.914
- I mean,
who needs "The Hunger Games"

14:31.958 --> 14:33.220
when you got high school,
am I right?

14:33.263 --> 14:36.527
[laughter]

14:36.571 --> 14:38.573
- I just wish they'd stop
talking about our son

14:38.616 --> 14:40.270
like there's something
wrong with him.

14:40.314 --> 14:42.577
You hear all these things,
you know.

14:42.620 --> 14:45.188
And you look at your kid,
and you just want

14:45.232 --> 14:47.147
to keep them safe
and see them happy.

14:47.190 --> 14:50.411
And some of these people just
want to make that impossible.

14:50.454 --> 14:51.978
And I'll tell you,

14:52.021 --> 14:54.894
I bet none of them have met
an actual trans kid.

14:54.937 --> 14:56.983
They make up this boogeyman,
you know,

14:57.026 --> 15:00.029
like they're some danger
that has to be stopped,

15:00.073 --> 15:03.772
when the only real danger
is us losing our children.

15:03.815 --> 15:05.992
But if they would just
pause for a second

15:06.035 --> 15:07.863
and get to know
some of these kids,

15:07.907 --> 15:10.953
maybe they would see
what we see--

15:10.997 --> 15:13.738
our babies,
growing up and changing,

15:13.782 --> 15:15.523
telling us who they are

15:15.566 --> 15:17.568
and who they want to be
in the world.

15:17.612 --> 15:19.788
Isn't that what we all want
for our kids?

15:19.831 --> 15:21.877
Doesn't every single child
deserve the right

15:21.921 --> 15:24.358
to become their own person,

15:24.401 --> 15:26.708
to shine their own light?

15:26.751 --> 15:28.710
Because I don't see
the harm in that.

15:28.753 --> 15:31.104
But I do see the harm
in trying to block it.

15:31.147 --> 15:32.453
[soft dramatic music]

15:32.496 --> 15:34.455
[laughter]

15:34.498 --> 15:41.636
♪

15:47.598 --> 15:49.557
[audio playing softly
on device]

15:49.600 --> 15:51.080
- They are pretty great.

15:51.124 --> 15:52.995
- [laughs]

15:53.039 --> 15:56.999
Yeah, trans kids
are absolute magic.

15:57.043 --> 15:59.219
I mean, once you give them
permission to just shine,

15:59.262 --> 16:00.220
they light up a room.

16:00.263 --> 16:02.396
The inverse is also true,

16:02.439 --> 16:04.311
of course,
when you try to force them

16:04.354 --> 16:05.834
to be something
that they're not.

16:05.877 --> 16:07.531
[soft dramatic music]

16:07.575 --> 16:09.142
- [sighs]

16:11.840 --> 16:13.363
Want to tell me
how you're holding up?

16:13.407 --> 16:17.237
♪

16:17.280 --> 16:20.675
- Look, I'm, um--
I'm gonna tell you something,

16:20.718 --> 16:23.199
because I think
if you don't hear it from me,

16:23.243 --> 16:27.116
then you might not notice it
in time for someone else.

16:27.160 --> 16:31.468
When I was a--a kid,

16:31.512 --> 16:33.949
I tried to take my own life.

16:33.993 --> 16:35.820
- Ian.

16:35.864 --> 16:37.257
- I mean, I was a--
I was a child.

16:37.300 --> 16:39.128
I wasn't even 13.

16:39.172 --> 16:42.914
And I think on the outside,

16:42.958 --> 16:46.788
everything just--
it seemed okay.

16:46.831 --> 16:50.139
You know, I was a--
I was a smart kid.

16:50.183 --> 16:52.446
Came from a loving family.

16:52.489 --> 16:57.799
But...I was alone,

16:57.842 --> 17:04.153
just f--floating
in this gray space,

17:04.196 --> 17:08.810
while everybody else was
in black and white.

17:08.853 --> 17:12.204
And when the entire world
just keeps telling you

17:12.248 --> 17:17.297
over and over again that people
like you are not worthy,

17:17.339 --> 17:19.473
you just--eventually,
you start to believe it.

17:19.516 --> 17:21.823
- You are so worthy.

17:21.866 --> 17:24.304
- [chuckles softly]

17:24.347 --> 17:25.435
I know.

17:25.479 --> 17:27.089
Oh, I know.

17:27.133 --> 17:32.138
My story, uh, it just--
it isn't special.

17:32.181 --> 17:37.752
Statistics say that one in five
trans kids attempt suicide.

17:37.795 --> 17:39.145
I was one of the lucky ones,
you know.

17:39.188 --> 17:40.363
I--I had a lifeline.

17:40.407 --> 17:43.584
I had, uh, the Coding Club.

17:43.627 --> 17:46.456
And for Gia,
that is obviously basketball.

17:46.500 --> 17:48.023
I mean, without it, she's lost.

17:48.067 --> 17:50.547
- But that only happens
if she runs away.

17:50.591 --> 17:51.940
And we can stop that.

17:51.983 --> 17:53.855
- Yeah.
Well, um, running away

17:53.898 --> 17:55.726
obviously looks different
for trans kids,

17:55.770 --> 17:57.163
so I had to create an equation

17:57.206 --> 18:00.688
that would factor in increased
risk of homelessness

18:00.731 --> 18:02.733
and of suicide and hate crimes.

18:02.777 --> 18:05.214
And that doesn't even account
for race or ability.

18:05.258 --> 18:07.869
- Ian.

18:07.912 --> 18:11.133
Thank you
for sharing your story.

18:11.177 --> 18:16.269
And if things
ever get dark again,

18:16.312 --> 18:19.315
please know that I will
be there for you,

18:19.359 --> 18:23.580
like you have been there
for me through all of this.

18:29.760 --> 18:32.502
[Carly Rae Jepsen's
"Call Me Maybe" playing]

18:32.546 --> 18:34.939
[indistinct chatter]

18:36.463 --> 18:37.507
- You want us to come with you?

18:37.551 --> 18:39.422
- Dad, gross.

18:39.466 --> 18:40.510
- Be careful.

18:40.554 --> 18:41.729
- Bye.

18:41.772 --> 18:42.730
- I want to follow her.

18:42.773 --> 18:43.861
- Don't be that dad.

18:50.433 --> 18:51.782
- I'm gonna follow her.

18:53.175 --> 18:55.046
- Hey!

18:55.090 --> 18:57.484
You made it!

18:57.527 --> 18:59.877
Mm.

18:59.921 --> 19:02.619
Yo, come to our station.

19:07.276 --> 19:10.584
- Oh, shoot, it's
Diana Taurasi in the flesh?

19:10.627 --> 19:12.151
- Uh-uh!
[laughs]

19:12.194 --> 19:14.588
- That final shot,
it's all anyone can talk about.

19:14.631 --> 19:16.329
- Yeah, I'm sure.
- No, for real.

19:16.372 --> 19:17.765
You were amazing.

19:17.808 --> 19:19.245
- Really?
Thanks.

19:19.288 --> 19:21.116
- Just make sure you bring it
to the game tomorrow,

19:21.160 --> 19:23.423
'cause Lions got to get
to regionals!

19:23.466 --> 19:26.339
[all cheering]

19:26.382 --> 19:28.428
- Hey, look,
we know you got the shots,

19:28.471 --> 19:30.734
but let's see if you can
handle these suds, all right?

19:30.778 --> 19:33.084
- Okay.
[laughter]

19:33.128 --> 19:35.609
- ♪ Hey, I just met you

19:35.652 --> 19:37.654
♪ And this is crazy

19:37.698 --> 19:39.482
♪ But here's my number

19:39.526 --> 19:41.136
♪ So call me maybe

19:41.180 --> 19:43.747
♪ It's hard to look right

19:43.791 --> 19:45.706
♪ At you, baby

19:45.749 --> 19:47.447
♪ But here's my number

19:47.490 --> 19:48.926
♪ So call me maybe

19:48.970 --> 19:50.145
[tires screech]

19:50.189 --> 19:51.364
- Hey, Gia!

19:51.407 --> 19:52.843
You'll never be a real girl.

19:52.887 --> 19:55.194
Forget your huevos?
[laughs]

19:55.237 --> 19:56.630
[kids shrieking]

19:56.673 --> 19:57.979
[laughing]

19:58.022 --> 20:00.155
Go, go, go!
Come on, drive.

20:00.199 --> 20:02.810
- Come back and say it
to my face, jackass!

20:02.853 --> 20:03.767
[dramatic music]

20:03.811 --> 20:05.465
[gasps]

20:05.508 --> 20:06.640
- What are you doing?

20:06.683 --> 20:07.815
That is my car!

20:07.858 --> 20:09.251
- I'm so sorry.
I didn't mean to.

20:09.295 --> 20:10.600
- Gia, are you okay?

20:10.644 --> 20:12.254
- Dad, what are you doing here?
- Mom and I were

20:12.298 --> 20:13.821
watching from the car.
- You were what?

20:13.864 --> 20:15.170
- We have a zero tolerance

20:15.214 --> 20:16.432
for violence policy
on this team.

20:16.476 --> 20:17.999
- Yeah, well, what's
your policy for bullying?

20:18.042 --> 20:19.914
- Let's just go, please.

20:19.957 --> 20:20.915
We're going.
- I'm calling the principal.

20:20.958 --> 20:22.264
She destroyed my property.

20:22.308 --> 20:23.526
- Gia.
- Ben.

20:23.570 --> 20:26.312
Ben, Ziggy found out
what happened to Gia.

20:26.355 --> 20:27.574
She dies out there alone.

20:27.617 --> 20:29.228
The police misgender her body.

20:29.271 --> 20:30.794
That's why there was no record.

20:30.838 --> 20:32.448
That's why her parents could
never stop looking for her.

20:32.492 --> 20:34.581
You have to stop her
from running away,

20:34.624 --> 20:36.191
or else she's gonna be erased.

20:36.235 --> 20:38.933
♪

20:42.328 --> 20:43.677
- Yes, we'll be there.

20:43.720 --> 20:46.245
[tense music]

20:46.288 --> 20:48.595
Principal Krager's called
an emergency meeting

20:48.638 --> 20:51.511
after school tomorrow
to "protect girls' basketball."

20:51.554 --> 20:52.512
- What does that even mean?

20:52.555 --> 20:54.209
- It means I am gonna have

20:54.253 --> 20:56.472
to find someone
to cover my shift.

20:56.516 --> 20:59.258
I am not gonna let
her threaten either of you.

20:59.301 --> 21:01.956
- Dad, are you gonna
lose your job?

21:01.999 --> 21:03.392
- Gia's right, Ben.

21:03.436 --> 21:05.089
Ziggy says
Carlos Mendez is fired.

21:05.133 --> 21:07.048
♪

21:07.091 --> 21:08.528
- No. We're gonna fight this.

21:08.571 --> 21:11.095
- Damn right,
we're gonna fight this.

21:11.139 --> 21:12.271
- Maybe I should just
quit the team.

21:12.314 --> 21:14.098
- What? No.

21:14.142 --> 21:15.752
- Dad, it's not worth it.

21:15.796 --> 21:16.797
I'm not even that good.

21:16.840 --> 21:18.059
- Hey, don't say that.

21:18.102 --> 21:20.583
Don't you ever say that.

21:22.759 --> 21:25.153
Gia, look, I know
high school can be tough, but--

21:25.196 --> 21:27.460
- Papá,
what would you even know?

21:27.503 --> 21:30.767
Mr. Star Athlete,
you were big man on campus.

21:30.811 --> 21:32.813
- Right.

21:32.856 --> 21:35.163
But I--

21:37.818 --> 21:41.038
Did I ever tell you
about my friend, Ben Song?

21:41.082 --> 21:45.086
He was this Korean kid
in a school full of white kids.

21:45.129 --> 21:48.481
And he also felt
very different and alone.

21:48.524 --> 21:51.788
- Dad, I bet it sucked
for Ben Song.

21:51.832 --> 21:56.184
But I have to fight every day
just to be who I know I am,

21:56.227 --> 21:59.361
while everyone else around me
tells me I'm someone else,

21:59.405 --> 22:01.320
even my own reflection.

22:05.454 --> 22:07.369
- And whenever I smell Febreze,

22:07.413 --> 22:09.110
I think of him.

22:09.153 --> 22:11.112
She called it loneliness,

22:11.155 --> 22:14.202
but I called it toast.

22:14.245 --> 22:15.334
Thank you.

22:18.293 --> 22:19.468
- I'm surprised
you actually agreed

22:19.512 --> 22:20.817
to come back here with me.

22:20.861 --> 22:21.905
- Are you kidding?

22:21.949 --> 22:23.080
I wouldn't miss this
for the world.

22:23.124 --> 22:24.517
- My final offering
this evening

22:24.560 --> 22:27.346
is a new choreopoem
I've been devising.

22:27.389 --> 22:28.999
And it's a work in process,

22:29.043 --> 22:30.697
as are we all,

22:30.740 --> 22:33.700
so thank you for your kindness.

22:38.269 --> 22:41.882
[loudly]
I gaze into the mirror...

22:45.102 --> 22:51.239
But my face doesn't know
who I am.

22:51.282 --> 22:53.807
I stare into the reflection

22:53.850 --> 22:57.158
of a future me
I could never be,

22:57.201 --> 23:01.162
and I realize, I am the other,

23:01.205 --> 23:03.730
and the other is me.

23:03.773 --> 23:05.819
I am another,

23:05.862 --> 23:10.345
and the other...is we.

23:10.389 --> 23:12.695
[applause]

23:12.739 --> 23:14.871
- Well, are you thinking
what I'm thinking?

23:14.915 --> 23:17.091
- I'm thinking we know
why Dottie doesn't

23:17.134 --> 23:19.528
remember meeting Ben.

23:22.139 --> 23:23.489
[door opens]

23:23.532 --> 23:26.448
[soft dramatic music]

23:26.492 --> 23:33.412
♪

23:36.415 --> 23:38.068
- Thank you for taking the time
to meet with me.

23:38.112 --> 23:40.462
I called you here today
because there has been

23:40.506 --> 23:44.684
significant community concern
that Gia's participation

23:44.727 --> 23:47.730
on the team is not fair
to the other girls.

23:47.774 --> 23:50.298
- Okay, let's not pretend
these complaints are anonymous.

23:50.341 --> 23:52.779
- Okay, I might be one parent,
but there are plenty of others

23:52.822 --> 23:54.302
that just aren't brave enough
to speak up.

23:54.345 --> 23:57.479
- Real brave, coming after
a girl your daughter's age.

23:57.523 --> 23:59.568
- Margie, we can
reimburse you for the damage.

23:59.612 --> 24:01.831
It was an accident.
- This isn't about my car.

24:01.875 --> 24:03.267
This is about
keeping Lakehill--

24:03.311 --> 24:06.401
- Have you gotten all
of your college apps in yet?

24:06.445 --> 24:07.881
- I'm just trying to get
through high school.

24:07.924 --> 24:10.144
So no, not really.

24:10.187 --> 24:12.799
- You're just doubling down
on excluding her.

24:12.842 --> 24:15.758
- When I was my daughter's age,
we didn't have girls' sports.

24:15.802 --> 24:18.021
We had to fight for Title IX.
So I'm not gonna sit here

24:18.065 --> 24:20.763
as you take away women's sports
because you think

24:20.807 --> 24:23.070
there's no difference
between boys and girls.

24:23.113 --> 24:25.551
- No one is taking
anything away from anyone.

24:25.594 --> 24:27.422
It's about inclusion.
- You call it inclusion,

24:27.466 --> 24:29.685
but who is gonna protect
mydaughter?

24:29.729 --> 24:32.993
- Margie, you have no idea

24:33.036 --> 24:35.299
what we have been through
as parents.

24:35.343 --> 24:38.041
Everything we have done
to keep our daughter safe--

24:38.085 --> 24:40.261
the doctors, the therapists,

24:40.304 --> 24:42.002
the lawyers, the church groups.

24:42.045 --> 24:44.613
- Oh, yeah.
What kind of church is that?

24:44.657 --> 24:47.921
- The kind that teaches
"gather the little children"

24:47.964 --> 24:51.533
and "do unto others as you
would have them do to you."

24:53.274 --> 24:55.015
- Can I ask you something?

24:55.058 --> 24:58.018
What if Shruti got scouted
for Stanford, and you didn't?

24:58.061 --> 24:59.976
- Shruti? Yeah, right.

25:00.020 --> 25:01.500
- I'm serious.

25:05.373 --> 25:07.636
- I guess I would be jealous,

25:07.680 --> 25:10.291
but, like, still proud of her.

25:10.334 --> 25:12.336
- What if it was me?

25:12.380 --> 25:15.122
What if I got a spot
instead of you?

25:17.167 --> 25:18.560
- You know that's different.

25:21.432 --> 25:23.565
What do you want me to say?

25:23.609 --> 25:25.611
- I want you to say
that you see me

25:25.654 --> 25:27.656
just like any other girl
on the team,

25:27.700 --> 25:30.224
that I deserve
a chance to play,

25:30.267 --> 25:32.922
that you want me out there
on the court getting open

25:32.966 --> 25:34.097
so we can win.

25:36.752 --> 25:39.450
- I--I can't say all of that.

25:41.365 --> 25:47.807
♪

25:47.850 --> 25:51.288
- Even at practice,
when we're just playing,

25:51.332 --> 25:53.856
do you really believe all that
"she's not one of us" stuff?

25:57.686 --> 26:02.125
- I mean,
we are on the same team.

26:02.169 --> 26:03.344
- Thank you.

26:03.387 --> 26:04.388
Hear that, y'all?

26:04.432 --> 26:06.826
Brandis and I are
on the same team.

26:06.869 --> 26:07.957
[both laugh]

26:08.001 --> 26:09.959
- I think it's better
for everyone

26:10.003 --> 26:11.874
if we put Gia back
on the bench.

26:11.918 --> 26:13.876
It's not appropriate
to force the school

26:13.920 --> 26:15.922
into this type
of political controversy.

26:15.965 --> 26:17.576
- Force the school?
We are talking

26:17.619 --> 26:19.055
about a child playing a game.

26:19.099 --> 26:20.448
- Whose decision was it
to put her

26:20.491 --> 26:21.580
on the team in the first place?

26:21.623 --> 26:23.103
- We discussed Gia being
on the team

26:23.146 --> 26:25.235
when the district offered
Carlos his coaching job.

26:25.279 --> 26:26.715
- Yes, we agreed

26:26.759 --> 26:29.631
that she could practice
with the girls privately.

26:29.675 --> 26:31.590
You broke that agreement
when you put your daughter

26:31.633 --> 26:32.895
out there on the court.

26:32.939 --> 26:34.636
- What?

26:36.290 --> 26:37.378
- Gia, please--

26:37.421 --> 26:38.771
- No!

26:38.814 --> 26:41.512
I thought you had my back,
no matter what.

26:41.556 --> 26:42.513
That's what you said.

26:42.557 --> 26:44.167
- I do. We do.

26:44.211 --> 26:46.605
- By making a deal with them
to keep me off the court?

26:46.648 --> 26:48.345
- We just tried
to keep you safe.

26:48.389 --> 26:50.130
You know how cruel
people can be.

26:50.173 --> 26:52.219
- You know what's cruel?

26:52.262 --> 26:54.525
Telling me to wait my turn,

26:54.569 --> 26:57.093
knowing this whole time
my turn was never gonna happen.

26:57.137 --> 26:59.269
- It's just
so much more complicated.

26:59.313 --> 27:02.011
- No. It's not.

27:02.055 --> 27:05.536
You lied to me.

27:05.580 --> 27:07.103
I hate you!

27:07.147 --> 27:12.631
♪

27:12.674 --> 27:14.633
- Gia!
- Gia!

27:14.676 --> 27:16.025
- Gia!
- Gia!

27:16.069 --> 27:17.461
- She took the van.
- Gia!

27:17.505 --> 27:19.725
[suspenseful music]

27:19.768 --> 27:21.770
Do you have any idea
where she would have gone?

27:21.814 --> 27:23.119
- No.
- Ben, Ziggy says

27:23.163 --> 27:24.294
if she makes it out
of the city--

27:24.338 --> 27:25.295
- I know, I know!

27:25.339 --> 27:26.470
- What do you know?

27:26.514 --> 27:27.863
- This is all my fault.

27:27.907 --> 27:29.125
- Hey.

27:29.169 --> 27:30.649
I need you to calm down

27:30.692 --> 27:33.129
and help me find our daughter,
all right?

27:33.173 --> 27:34.653
- All right.

27:34.696 --> 27:36.655
Okay.
[laughs wryly]

27:36.698 --> 27:39.135
This actually isn't
my first runaway kid, so.

27:40.571 --> 27:41.790
[indistinctly] Yeah, yeah.

27:41.834 --> 27:42.922
Where are her favorite places,

27:42.965 --> 27:44.706
somewhere she likes
to hang out?

27:44.750 --> 27:45.968
- We don't let her hang out.

27:46.012 --> 27:47.970
- Right.
We don't let her hang out.

27:48.014 --> 27:49.668
Uh, is there somewhere
she would go?

27:49.711 --> 27:52.540
Anyone she would call?

27:52.583 --> 27:53.715
Give me your phone.

27:53.759 --> 27:56.849
♪

28:01.157 --> 28:02.550
- Do you realize
what you're asking me to do?

28:02.593 --> 28:03.943
- Just give me enough
for the first couple weeks.

28:03.986 --> 28:05.727
I'll get a job,
and I'll pay you back, I swear.

28:05.771 --> 28:07.686
- You'll get a job.
That's your big plan?

28:07.729 --> 28:09.339
And you'll find
a place to live too?

28:09.383 --> 28:11.211
A 17-year-old trans girl
out there with nothing.

28:11.254 --> 28:12.342
- That's what you did.

28:12.386 --> 28:14.518
- Gia, I didn't have a choice.

28:14.562 --> 28:16.216
You have parents who love you.

28:16.259 --> 28:17.434
They may not get it right
all the time,

28:17.478 --> 28:18.522
but they're putting
in the work.

28:18.566 --> 28:20.873
- I just want
to live my own life.

28:20.916 --> 28:22.526
- Okay, real talk,

28:22.570 --> 28:24.485
if you think that running
around in these streets

28:24.528 --> 28:26.530
is the same thing
as independence,

28:26.574 --> 28:28.445
you might want to look again
at that definition.

28:28.489 --> 28:30.665
- I just want everyone to stop
hovering over me all the time,

28:30.709 --> 28:32.754
making decisions for me
about everything!

28:32.798 --> 28:34.625
- I get it. It's rough.

28:34.669 --> 28:36.018
I know.

28:36.062 --> 28:37.454
But at the same time, doll,

28:37.498 --> 28:40.414
I have to tell you,
a lot of these kids out here,

28:40.457 --> 28:42.721
they don't have this luxury.

28:42.764 --> 28:43.722
[sighs]

28:43.765 --> 28:45.593
I talked to your parents.

28:45.636 --> 28:46.986
- [huffs, scoffs]

28:47.029 --> 28:49.292
[tense music]

28:49.336 --> 28:52.513
♪

28:52.556 --> 28:53.775
- I told them I'd wait with you

28:53.819 --> 28:55.516
till they get here,
if that's okay.

28:55.559 --> 28:57.736
- Am I gonna get in trouble?

28:57.779 --> 29:00.739
- I think everybody's just glad
you came here first.

29:00.782 --> 29:01.783
I know I am.

29:11.445 --> 29:14.448
- Were you out in high school?

29:14.491 --> 29:17.190
- Uh, those are two
different questions.

29:17.233 --> 29:18.582
Was I out?

29:18.626 --> 29:19.540
Oh, yeah.

29:19.583 --> 29:21.847
Couldn't hide me. [chuckles]

29:21.890 --> 29:22.978
Uh, was I in school?

29:23.022 --> 29:24.806
No.

29:24.850 --> 29:28.767
That wasn't a path
that seemed available to me.

29:31.857 --> 29:33.728
- What did you do?

29:33.772 --> 29:35.948
- I did what we all did
back then,

29:35.991 --> 29:37.471
relied on my trans sisters,

29:37.514 --> 29:40.430
and some aunties and guncles
along the way.

29:40.474 --> 29:43.085
No sugar daddies though,
unfortunately.

29:43.129 --> 29:44.347
- [chuckles]

29:47.611 --> 29:49.831
Were you part
of a ballroom house?

29:49.875 --> 29:51.441
- Oh, yeah, I was.

29:51.485 --> 29:52.834
- What was it like?
- Well, it wasn't

29:52.878 --> 29:55.054
all "Drag Race" or anything,
I'll tell you that much.

29:55.097 --> 29:56.969
We, uh, took care
of each other.

29:57.012 --> 30:00.146
It was mostly trans folk
kicked out from their homes,

30:00.189 --> 30:03.323
surviving on pennies
and voguing on down.

30:03.366 --> 30:09.111
But we also had a plague
to deal with, so.

30:09.155 --> 30:11.461
- How'd you do it?

30:11.505 --> 30:13.463
- You just get through
the hard times

30:13.507 --> 30:16.336
with the family that you got

30:16.379 --> 30:19.382
or the family that you make
along the way.

30:19.426 --> 30:21.820
[soft dramatic music]

30:21.863 --> 30:23.996
- Or maybe both?

30:24.039 --> 30:25.954
- Absolutely both.

30:25.998 --> 30:28.696
♪

30:28.739 --> 30:31.264
[car approaching]

30:32.918 --> 30:34.267
- Gia!

30:36.138 --> 30:38.793
I am so sorry, honey.

30:38.837 --> 30:40.142
I am so, so sorry.

30:40.186 --> 30:41.578
- Umma.

30:41.622 --> 30:44.320
- I--I didn't realize
we were making things worse.

30:44.364 --> 30:46.235
We were just trying
to protect you.

30:46.279 --> 30:49.325
- You said when the time
was right, but you knew.

30:49.369 --> 30:51.153
- Well, maybe the time
was right, kiddo.

30:51.197 --> 30:53.721
- You wouldn't have put me in
if you didn't have to.

30:53.764 --> 30:55.418
- Gia, n-no.
Maybe we might have

30:55.462 --> 30:56.811
made some mistakes,
but your mom and I,

30:56.855 --> 30:58.160
we were just trying
to keep you safe.

30:58.204 --> 30:59.945
- But you make the rules,

30:59.988 --> 31:01.511
you and Principal Krager

31:01.555 --> 31:03.862
and Amanda's mom
and everyone else.

31:03.905 --> 31:05.951
Why can't you grown-ups
just figure out

31:05.994 --> 31:09.041
how to make school safe
for everyone?

31:09.084 --> 31:12.696
- Listen, we don't want you

31:12.740 --> 31:15.743
to have to carry this burden
on your own.

31:15.786 --> 31:17.571
- Hey, look,

31:17.614 --> 31:20.879
maybe if you stop seeing
her transness as a burden,

31:20.922 --> 31:23.098
then she won't
feel like one, okay?

31:23.142 --> 31:26.406
You've raised a loving
and joyful child who's known

31:26.449 --> 31:29.061
what it's like to walk
in somebody else's shoes

31:29.104 --> 31:30.497
from a very young age.

31:30.540 --> 31:33.369
And you don't keep
your gorgeous trans child safe

31:33.413 --> 31:35.545
by hiding them away.

31:35.589 --> 31:38.200
You keep her safe by telling
her that you love her

31:38.244 --> 31:41.377
and by reassuring her that
you're gonna have her back,

31:41.421 --> 31:43.640
no matter what.

31:43.684 --> 31:46.730
- And by letting her play.

31:46.774 --> 31:50.169
I need you to start
letting me live my life,

31:50.212 --> 31:53.737
to play basketball and
to hang out with my friends,

31:53.781 --> 31:56.827
to stay out too late
and make mistakes.

31:58.307 --> 32:01.136
I know you're scared,

32:01.180 --> 32:06.663
and I'm sorry it's so scary
being parents of a trans kid.

32:06.707 --> 32:08.622
But you've got to get over it,

32:08.665 --> 32:12.974
because your fear is not
my responsibility.

32:15.629 --> 32:20.373
Thank you for letting me
be myself.

32:20.416 --> 32:22.853
But now you just have
to let me be a kid.

32:22.897 --> 32:29.817
♪

32:33.473 --> 32:35.779
- I'm sorry.

32:35.823 --> 32:37.172
Okay. All right.

32:37.216 --> 32:38.608
We will.

32:40.045 --> 32:42.961
And I believe we have
a basketball game to get to,

32:43.004 --> 32:44.136
if you're up for it.

32:44.179 --> 32:46.965
- But what about your job?

32:47.008 --> 32:51.012
- Being your parents is
the most important job we have.

32:54.059 --> 32:55.364
- Come on.

32:58.324 --> 33:01.327
[hopeful music]

33:01.370 --> 33:08.464
♪

33:10.510 --> 33:11.990
- We've got you, girl.

33:13.382 --> 33:14.731
Let's go.

33:21.956 --> 33:24.828
- 'Ey, you're done going into
that janitor's closet, Mendez.

33:24.872 --> 33:27.222
Girls' locker room is
for all girls, period.

33:27.266 --> 33:29.094
- Mm-hmm.
- What about your mom?

33:29.137 --> 33:31.792
- I told her she should let
us decide who we change with.

33:31.835 --> 33:33.837
- And I told her
the alternative is making

33:33.881 --> 33:36.492
the school nurse give us all
blood tests and strip searches.

33:36.536 --> 33:38.146
- Yo! They would do that to us?

33:38.190 --> 33:40.105
- They do it to Black women
all the time.

33:40.148 --> 33:41.758
- Adults are so weird, I swear.

33:41.802 --> 33:43.064
[all chuckle and agree]

33:43.108 --> 33:45.501
- So what I want to know is,

33:45.545 --> 33:47.068
are we a team?

33:47.112 --> 33:48.504
- Not without Gia.

33:48.548 --> 33:50.550
[all cheer]
- Ooh! I like that.

33:50.593 --> 33:52.421
'Ey! Are we a team?

33:52.465 --> 33:54.554
all: Not without Gia!

33:54.597 --> 33:56.382
[chanting]
Not without Gia!

33:56.425 --> 33:59.385
Not without Gia!
Not without Gia!

33:59.428 --> 34:01.082
Not without Gia!

34:01.126 --> 34:03.867
Not without Gia!

34:03.911 --> 34:05.347
- Coach, you got
your starting order?

34:05.391 --> 34:06.609
- Yeah, right here.

34:06.653 --> 34:08.568
- [exhales]
You sure about this?

34:08.610 --> 34:10.351
- Oh, yeah.

34:10.396 --> 34:11.614
- Right on.

34:11.658 --> 34:13.529
[dramatic music]

34:13.572 --> 34:15.966
- You're really gonna put your
job on the line for this stunt?

34:16.010 --> 34:17.925
- You might not be willing
to stand up for my daughter,

34:17.967 --> 34:19.882
but I've got a locker room
full of screaming girls

34:19.927 --> 34:21.146
who aren't playing this game
without her.

34:21.188 --> 34:22.538
- What exactly do you think

34:22.581 --> 34:24.192
you're going to achieve
with this?

34:24.235 --> 34:26.020
- Well, ma'am,

34:26.063 --> 34:28.456
I think we're about
to go to regionals.

34:28.501 --> 34:35.638
♪

34:37.118 --> 34:40.078
[crowd cheering]

34:40.121 --> 34:47.085
♪

34:50.262 --> 34:51.610
[whistle blows]

34:55.702 --> 34:57.312
[whistle blows]

34:57.356 --> 35:00.141
[crowd cheering]

35:00.185 --> 35:03.188
[dramatic music]

35:03.231 --> 35:04.624
- Agh.

35:04.667 --> 35:06.104
- Wake up, Gia, wake up.

35:10.238 --> 35:12.501
- Get under.
- It's okay, draw it out.

35:12.545 --> 35:13.546
Draw it out.

35:19.856 --> 35:21.554
- Ugh.
- Come on, Gia.

35:21.597 --> 35:22.555
Where's your head at?

35:22.598 --> 35:29.562
♪

35:34.175 --> 35:36.656
Gia, go. Hustle around!

35:36.699 --> 35:38.048
- Ugh!

35:40.094 --> 35:41.095
- All right.
Time out, time out!

35:41.139 --> 35:43.010
[whistle blows]
Circle up, Lions.

35:44.490 --> 35:45.665
Gia, what's wrong?

35:45.708 --> 35:47.188
- Why did they let
those people in here?

35:47.232 --> 35:48.798
[crowd jeering]
- Don't worry about them.

35:48.842 --> 35:51.192
Just a few haters
out of how many?

35:51.236 --> 35:53.716
Look how many people are here
cheering for you.

35:53.760 --> 35:57.067
[crowd cheering]

35:57.111 --> 35:59.896
[inspirational music]

35:59.940 --> 36:02.551
♪

36:02.595 --> 36:05.641
Listen, you've earned
your spot on this team,

36:05.685 --> 36:07.077
all of you.

36:07.121 --> 36:09.341
And no matter what happens
from this point out,

36:09.384 --> 36:11.734
win or lose, regionals or not,

36:11.778 --> 36:14.563
I want you to give it
everything you've got.

36:14.607 --> 36:16.739
Basketball is no different
from the rest of your life.

36:16.783 --> 36:21.179
You define the game
by how you choose to play it.

36:21.222 --> 36:23.964
So show up.
Put your whole heart into it.

36:24.007 --> 36:25.922
Try and work hard as a team,

36:25.966 --> 36:28.229
but do not back down,

36:28.273 --> 36:30.753
especially when you know
what's right.

36:30.797 --> 36:36.498
♪

36:36.542 --> 36:39.588
[crowd cheering]

36:39.632 --> 36:42.417
Now, what do Lions do?

36:42.461 --> 36:43.288
- We roar!

36:43.331 --> 36:45.768
- I said, what do Lions do?

36:45.812 --> 36:49.294
all: We roar!

36:51.383 --> 36:53.689
- Get open.
I'll pass it to you.

36:53.733 --> 36:56.518
Show them what you can do.

36:56.562 --> 36:58.433
[whistle blows]

36:58.477 --> 37:04.570
♪

37:10.010 --> 37:11.011
- Whoo!

37:11.054 --> 37:14.188
[cheers and applause]

37:15.668 --> 37:17.887
- Hey.

37:17.931 --> 37:19.541
You wanna watch the game?

37:19.585 --> 37:22.414
- Are you--
are you serious right now?

37:22.457 --> 37:24.416
- Come on.
- This is so against the rules.

37:24.459 --> 37:27.157
- Hey, I am just
holding a door open.

37:28.594 --> 37:30.639
- Accomplice.

37:30.683 --> 37:32.032
You're an accomplice.

37:34.774 --> 37:40.258
♪

37:40.301 --> 37:41.650
- Yes, yes! There you go!

37:41.694 --> 37:43.391
- Let's go, Gia!

37:43.435 --> 37:44.871
- Is that your daughter?
- Yes!

37:44.914 --> 37:45.915
- She's awesome.

37:45.959 --> 37:47.830
- She really is.

37:47.874 --> 37:50.355
- This is incredible.

37:50.398 --> 37:51.443
- Yeah.

37:56.361 --> 37:57.666
- The principal wanted me
to come tell you

37:57.710 --> 38:00.582
to pull your daughter,
but I can't do that.

38:00.626 --> 38:03.193
School sports are meant
to teach students life skills,

38:03.237 --> 38:04.456
to build their confidence,
and show them

38:04.499 --> 38:06.022
how to work together as a team.

38:06.066 --> 38:09.939
I never want to keep any child
from that experience.

38:09.983 --> 38:11.027
- Thank you.

38:11.071 --> 38:13.813
- Also, I'm the union rep.

38:13.856 --> 38:16.859
They try and fire you,
we got your back--

38:16.903 --> 38:18.513
and Gia's.

38:23.039 --> 38:28.175
- ♪ You just gotta
ignite the light ♪

38:28.218 --> 38:31.787
♪ And let it shine

38:31.831 --> 38:35.530
- Yes!
- ♪ Just own the night

38:35.574 --> 38:38.925
♪ Like the Fourth of July

38:38.968 --> 38:43.364
♪ 'Cause baby,
you're a firework ♪

38:43.408 --> 38:46.541
♪ Come on,
let your colors burst ♪

38:46.585 --> 38:50.023
♪ Make 'em go, ah, ah, ah

38:50.066 --> 38:55.463
♪ You're gonna leave 'em all
in awe, awe, awe ♪

38:55.507 --> 38:58.031
♪ Boom, boom, boom

38:58.074 --> 39:00.816
♪ Even brighter
than the moon, moon, moon ♪

39:00.860 --> 39:01.817
- Go, Gia!

39:01.861 --> 39:03.384
♪

39:03.428 --> 39:05.647
- ♪ Boom, boom, boom

39:05.691 --> 39:07.301
♪ Even brighter
than the moon ♪

39:07.345 --> 39:08.955
- Nice assist!

39:08.998 --> 39:11.218
♪

39:11.261 --> 39:13.525
- ♪ Boom, boom, boom

39:13.568 --> 39:17.790
♪ Even brighter
than the moon, moon, moon ♪

39:17.833 --> 39:19.139
♪

39:19.182 --> 39:20.140
- Ah!

39:20.183 --> 39:23.317
[crowd cheering]

39:25.841 --> 39:28.757
[tense music]

39:28.801 --> 39:30.455
♪

39:30.498 --> 39:33.545
- Those feelings
you describe in your poem,

39:33.588 --> 39:36.722
that face you kept seeing,

39:36.765 --> 39:38.941
I had an experience
like that too.

39:38.985 --> 39:41.204
- I lost time.

39:41.248 --> 39:42.902
The week you say
that photo was taken,

39:42.945 --> 39:44.556
I just don't remember.

39:44.599 --> 39:47.515
- Wow.
What if I told you,

39:47.559 --> 39:50.866
you were right about a secret
government conspiracy,

39:50.910 --> 39:53.303
something you were
all wrapped up in,

39:53.347 --> 39:54.609
but didn't even know about?

39:54.653 --> 39:56.306
- I'd tell you, I told you so.

39:56.350 --> 40:00.180
- Let's say you did
lose time for a week.

40:00.223 --> 40:01.442
To everyone else,
you were still Dottie,

40:01.486 --> 40:03.183
doing everything Dottie does.

40:03.226 --> 40:06.578
But did you ever stop to think

40:06.621 --> 40:09.798
about who was behind the wheel,

40:09.842 --> 40:13.323
who was driving you
like a bus the whole time?

40:13.367 --> 40:14.586
- Are you kidding?

40:14.629 --> 40:16.152
I can't get them
out of my head.

40:16.196 --> 40:17.676
I just, uh--

40:19.852 --> 40:21.157
I just keep drawing them.

40:21.201 --> 40:28.338
♪

40:28.382 --> 40:30.515
- This is the person
you see in your dreams?

40:32.299 --> 40:33.909
- That's the person
